Vheadline
p2
VHomage to a guru
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe Vinayaka Chathurthi festival conducted by the Sri Nandrudayan Sangeetha Samajam, Tiruchi, coincided with the birth centenary of Palani M. Subramania Pillai, mridangam and ganjira wizard.  Pillai took active part in the temple festival from 1940 to 1961 without a break accompanying stalwart musicians of those days.The festival commenced with the flute recital by N. Ramani.Ramani spoke a few words about Pillai&#8217;s greatness as an artist. It was followed by an audio play of Pillai&#8217;s  thani avarthanam at a concert in 1950&#8217;s.  Ramani&#8217;s recital began with a varnam in Sriragam followed by Tyagaraja&#8217;s &#8216;Paramathmudu&#8217; in the raga Vagatheeswari as a main song with an elaboration of the  raga before commencing the main song.The second day featured a speech on Pillai by Professor S. Thyagarajan   followed by Sikkil Gurucharan&#8217;s  vocal recital.He sang &#8216;Sri Vathapi Ganapathiye&#8217; in the raga Sahana by briefly elaborating the raga and then he took up Tyagaraja&#8217;s  &#8216;Rajuvedala Joothamurare,&#8217;  in raga Thodi with a neat elaboration of the raga.Veena recital by Sivakumar formed the third day&#8217;s programme.Sivakumar took up raga Khambodi  for elaboration and rendered Tyagarja&#8217;s &#8216;Evarimata.&#8217;  The concert was preceded by a brief speech about Pillai by Vidwan R. Thayumanavan, himself being a laya exponent.Master M. Balamuralikrishna gave a pleasing vocal recital on the next day. His &#8216;Mathisallaka&#8217; in Anandabhairavi and &#8216;Sri Kanthani&#8217; in Bhavapriya were superb.On September 8, A. Venkatraman, leading adviser on finances, spoke about his personal experiences with Pillai when the latter used to stay at their house in Kolkata  while on a  concert tour along with legends of  Carnatic music of those days.Later T.M. Krishna gave an excellent account of himself as a vocalist delineating ragas Harikhambodi and Hamsadhwani followed by the kriti, &#8216;Enthuku&#8217; of Saint Tyagaraja and &#8216;Vathapi&#8217; of Dikshitar. Towards the end of the concert his rendering of &#8216;Varuvaro&#8217; in  Sama was excellent.Amrutha Sankaranarayanan, daughter and disciple of veteran vocalist T. V. Sanakaranarayanan, gave a pleasant vocal recital on September 9. Her  rendering of &#8216;Kanakankodi Vendum&#8217; in  Khambodi was superb.T. V. Sankaranarayanan enthralled the audience  the next day.  He presented  &#8216;Chakkaniraja&#8217; of Tyagaraja.Earlier, T.V. Sanakaranarayanan made a brief speech about Pillai and the regards he had for the family of late Madurai Mani Iyer.O. S. Thyagarajan&#8217;s recital and his elaboration of raga Kapi were scintillating.  Shertalai K.N. Renganatha Sarma gave a pleasing vocal concert on September 12.The programme on Septermber 13, featured the violin recitals of Lalgudi G.J.R. Krishnan and Vijayalakshmi. The programme also had Krishnan reading out a message sent by his father and guru Lalgudi  G. Jayaraman, which elaborated his long association with Pillai who encouraged him in his (Lalgudi&#8217;s) formative years.Vijayalakshmi enthralled the listeners with her Kharaharapriya raga elaboration followed by the song &#8216;Samanamevaru,&#8217; by  Tyagaraja.Krishnan&#8217;s rendition of Kalyani as the main raga was well received by the audience.  It was followed by Dikshitar&#8217;s  &#8216;Kamalamba Bajare.&#8217;On September 14 after a brief speech by Trichur V. Ramachandran on  Pillai wherein he reminisced on Pillai accompanying his Guru GNB and the type of regards and affection each had for the other.This was followed by his rendition of &#8216;Bhajare Manasa&#8217; in  Karnataka Devakanthari preceded by an elaborate raga elaboration.Tiruchi Sankaran, one of the senior disciples of Pillai, sent a message where in he recalled his debut in 1955 in a  temple festival where Alathur Brothers were the vocalists with Lalgudi Jayaraman on the violin, Pillai and Sankaran on the mridangam.The essence of the message was a real homage to his guru. This was followed b a pleasing vocal recital by Neyveli Santhanagopalan. The festival concluded with T. V. Ramprasadh&#8217;s vocal concert.His Ketharagowla raga elaboration followed by thanam and pallavi were well received by the discerning audience.
